# .worktreeinclude — gitignored entries to bring INTO a new worktree.
#
# `git worktree add` checks out TRACKED files only, so a worktree is lean by
# default (no target/, node_modules/, .repos/). This file lists the gitignored,
# untracked things a worktree may still need; scripts/new-worktree.ts copies or
# symlinks each one in after creating the worktree.
#
# Format: one entry per line. Blank lines and `#` comments are ignored.
#   [copy|symlink] <path>      path is relative to the repo root (both sides)
# The leading verb is optional; the default is `copy`. Use `symlink` for large,
# read-only things you don't want duplicated on disk.
#
# Do NOT list target/ here — cargo's incremental fingerprints are keyed to the
# absolute target path, so a copied/symlinked target dir is invalidated and
# rebuilt from scratch. The fast loop is a stable, dedicated per-worktree
# CARGO_TARGET_DIR (new-worktree.ts prints the convention), not a seeded one.

# Read-only reference checkouts of other runtimes/tools (node, bun, pnpm, …).
# Symlinked so worktree agents can Read/Grep them without a multi-GB copy.
symlink .repos

# fray orchestration control surface. Symlinked so a worktree-isolated sub-agent
# can Edit its OWN .fray/<slug>.md thread (write-ownership) instead of the
# orchestrator re-transcribing it. .fray/ is gitignored so it's absent in a fresh
# worktree, and the Edit tool's sandbox blocks an absolute shared-tree path from
# inside a worktree — but writes THROUGH this symlink land in the real shared file
# (the sandbox check is path-prefix based and doesn't resolve symlinks).
# NOTE: this covers SCRIPTED worktrees (new-worktree.ts). HARNESS-created
# isolation:worktree worktrees do NOT run new-worktree.ts — those rely on the
# dispatch-prompt step-0 `ln -s <abs-shared-root>/.fray .fray`.
symlink .fray
